recount the intensity of personal struggles, and above all his fascination with the trials and tribulations of Love, which affect some of the work's most prominent warriors (among them Paris and his love for Helen, and Troilusand his love for Briseida), all combine to fashion this romance - in which events from long ago are presented as a reflection of the poet's own feudal and courtly worlds. This translation, the first into English, aims to bring the poem and the author to a wider audience. It is accompanied by an introduction and notes. Glyn S. Burgess is Emeritus Professor of French at the University of Liverpool; Douglas Kelly is Emeritus Professor of French and Medieval Studies at the University of Wisconsin-Madison.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrench literatureyTo 1500vTranslations into English. 0aFrench poetryyTo 1500vTranslations into English. 0aTrojan WarvLegends. 4aFrench Studies. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEnglish.  aanalysis.  acharacteristics.  agenre.  ahistory.  alinguistics.  aliterary analysis.  aliterature.  amiddle ages.  apoetry.  aprotagonist.  aroman history.  aromance.  arome.  astrategy.  atwelfth century.1 aBurgess, Glyn S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178744025840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440258423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440258/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles